name: New York Indian Council (NYIC)
address: While a specific street address for direct services isn't listed, they serve all five boroughs of New York City. Their administrative office is located at 175 East 116th Street, New York, NY 10029
description: The NYIC is New York City's Urban Indian Health Program, offering culturally informed health services, including primary care, specialty treatment, dental, and behavioral health services. They also assist with health insurance enrollment, including Medicaid

name: Address:
description: The SNHS provides comprehensive health services to eligible Native Americans within their service area, including medical, dental, optical, behavioral health, and more. They operate under federal and tribal guidelines and aim to serve the community's changing needs

name: Shinnecock Nation Health Services
description: Offers Purchased & Referred Care (PRC) services for healthcare needs not available at IHS or Tribal facilities. PRC funding is a payor of last resort, meaning it's available after other resources like Medicaid have been utilized

name: American Indian Health Program (New York State Department of Health)
address: This program coordinates services for nine recognized American Indian Nations in New York State. Specific clinic locations vary by Nation. Contact information for the program is AIHP.program@health.ny.gov
description: This program is responsible for providing access to medical care, dental care, and preventive health education for Native Americans in New York. Services are provided through contract agreements, direct payment, and direct contracts with Nations

name: Mohawk Networks LLC
address: Bombay, NY 12914 (This is a business entity, specific service addresses may vary)
description: While primarily listed as a media company, it's a tribally owned enterprise of the Saint Regis Mohawk Tribe. It's important to verify if they offer or facilitate Medicaid-related healthcare services

name: Seneca Nation of Indians Federal Credit Union (SNIFCU)
description: While a financial institution, it is owned by the Seneca Nation of Indians and supports the community. It's worth inquiring if they have any partnerships or resources related to healthcare access or Medicaid

name: Seneca One Stops
address: Multiple locations across Seneca Nation territories (e.g., Salamanca, Irving, Buffalo)
description: These are gas and convenience stores owned by the Seneca Nation of Indians. While not direct healthcare providers, their revenue supports Nation programs, which may include health services

name: Indian Health Service (IHS) Facilities Map
address: Various locations across New York State. The IHS provides a map to find facilities
description: This is a resource to locate Indian Health Service, Tribal, or Urban Indian Health Program facilities. These facilities often serve individuals eligible for Medicaid

name: New York State Department of Health - Tribal Health Clinic Information
address: Information pertains to tribal consultation for health clinics across New York State
description: This page discusses the New York State Department of Health's engagement with tribal entities regarding Medicaid State Plan Amendments, indicating a framework for tribal health services within the state's Medicaid system
